ou%20should%20have%20three%20to%20six%20months%20of%20expenses%20in%20savings.%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EBut%20I%20wiped%20out%20my%20emergency%20savings%20years%20ago%20and%20have%20no%20regrets.%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EI%20have%20plenty%20of%20money%20invested%2C%20and%20I'd%20rather%20let%20it%20grow%20there%20than%20sit%20in%20a%20savings%20account.%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3EAs%20a%20financial%20writer%20who%20frequently%20interviews%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fbest-online-financial-advisors%5C%22%3Efinancial%20advisors%3C%2Fa%3E%20about%20emergency%20funds%2C%20I%20have%20been%20told%20over%20and%20over%20again%20that%20%3Cem%3Eeveryone%3C%2Fem%3E%20should%20have%20three%20to%20six%20months%20of%20expenses%20stashed%20away%20in%20a%20bank%20account%20they%20can%20quickly%20and%20easily%20access.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20did%20that%20for%20quite%20a%20while%2C%20but%20I%20depleted%20my%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fwhat-is-an-emergency-fund%5C%22%3Eemergency%20fund%3C%2Fa%3E%20a%20few%20years%20ago%20and%20have%20never%2C%20ever%20looked%20back.%20Here's%20why%20this%20strategy%20has%20left%20me%20better%20off%20so%20far.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E1.%20I%20have%20easy%20access%20to%20credit%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EI%20have%20always%20been%20told%20that%20I%20need%20an%20emergency%20fund%20in%20case%20my%20car%20breaks%20down%20or%20I%20face%20unexpected%20medical%20bills%20or%20other%20surprise%20costs%20I%20didn't%20specifically%20save%20for.%20However%2C%20I%20use%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fbest-rewards-credit-cards%5C%22%3Erewards%20credit%20cards%3C%2Fa%3E%20faithfully%20and%20pay%20down%20my%20balances%20to%20%240%20every%20month.%20Due%20to%20my%20excellent%20credit%20score%2C%20I%20also%20have%20six%20figures%20in%20available%20open%20credit%20at%20any%20given%20time.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20I%20had%20a%20true%20%26quot%3Bemergency%26quot%3B%20expense%2C%20I%20would%20probably%20charge%20it%20to%20my%20credit%20card%20to%20earn%20rewards%20anyway.%20I%20never%2C%20ever%20want%20to%20pay%20interest%20on%20my%20purchases%2C%20but%20this%20would%20buy%20me%20some%20time%20to%20access%20the%20cash%20I%20need%20to%20pay%20off%20the%20debt%20before%20my%20credit%20card's%20due%20date.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E2.%20We%20have%20ample%20assets%20outside%20retirement%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20husband%20and%20I%20save%20for%20retirement%20in%20solo%20401(k)%20accounts%20with%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fvanguard-investing-review%5C%22%3EVanguard%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20but%20we%20also%20invest%20our%20extra%20funds%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fhow-to-invest-in-index-funds%5C%22%3Eindex%20funds%3C%2Fa%3E%20every%20month.%20By%20and%20large%2C%20this%20is%20the%20main%20reason%20I%20depleted%20our%20emergency%20fund.%20We%20%3Cem%3Edo%20%3C%2Fem%3Ehave%20extra%20money%20we%20could%20use%20in%20an%20emergency.%20We%20would%20just%20have%20to%20sell%20investments%20(and%20pay%20taxes)%20to%20use%20it.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20I%20am%20very%20happy%20with%20the%20trade-off%20I%20have%20made%20here.%20Where%20I%20could%20have%20had%20%2425%2C000%20sitting%20in%20a%20bank%20account%20earning%20a%20low%20APY%2C%20I%20invested%20my%20emergency%20fund%20in%20the%20Vanguard%20Total%20Stock%20Market%20Index%20Fund%20(VTSAX)%2C%20which%20has%20a%20three-year%20return%20of%20over%2021%25.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20I%20would%20owe%20the%20tax%20man%20if%20I%20had%20to%20sell%20investments%20to%20cover%20emergency%20expenses%2C%20the%20return%20I%20have%20earned%20makes%20this%20sacrifice%20well%20worth%20it.%20Also%2C%20note%20that%20I%20have%3Cem%3E%20not%20%3C%2Fem%3Eneeded%20to%20access%20this%20money%20since%20I%20depleted%20my%20emergency%20fund.%20If%20I%20can%20keep%20my%20money%20invested%20and%20growing%20without